<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-061-188 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 115 513</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Magazine  Sept 10 1991 v10 n15 p38(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM relaunches the touch display, this time for multimedia.andO;(Hardware Review) (IBM PS/2 Touch Display 8516) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ross, Matthew J.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>IBM's new PS/2 Touch Display 8516 is designed for multimediaapplications and does not use the overlays that slowed anddistorted earlier touch-screen units.andP;  Its pressure-transducermechanism works with any input device and does not require aspecial adapter, working with any standard VGA or XGA board.andP;  Thetransducers are located at each corner of the screen and reportthe touch location as x,y coordinates and the amount of appliedpressure as a z coordinate.andP;  Performance is good; the 8516operates smoothly with both mouse and touch-screen softwaredrivers.andP;  The Touch Display 8516 will be available in Sep 1991 for$1,695.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM PS/2 8516 Touch Screen (Monitor, color) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Multimedia technologyEvaluationMonitorsTouch Screens.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Fact file. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The last time IBM introduced a touch-screen display for PCs, it was anovelty.andP;  Now touch screens are more prevalent, especially on automatedteller machines.andP;  This time, IBM is aiming touch screens at the multimediamarket.andM;The PS/2 Touch Display 8516 does not use the overlays that slowed down anddistorted the color earlier.andP;  It doesn't even need a special adapter; astandard VGA or XGA adapter and a PS/2 mouse port suffices.andP;  And the touchmechanism works with any input device--your finger, a pen, pencil, etc.andM;Pressure transducers at each corner of its screen report the exact (x,y)touch location and the amount of applied pressure (the z coordinate).andO;Developers can create touch-screen applications that use three dimensions,using the degree of pressure as a criteria in user input.andM;The touch area equals the resolution of the display: either VGA or XGA.andP;  The8516 monitor also works as a touch screen with IBM's 8514/A, but only at VGAresolution.andM;The display connects to a PS/2 in two places: Video output comes through theVGA or XGA adapter and the user input is transmitted to the PS/2 mouse port.andO;A PS/2 mouse can be connected to the 8516's mouse port.andP;  Data is interleaved,so both remain active.andM;We tested the touch screen under OS/2, Version 1.3, on the new PS/2 Model 57SX.andP;  It operated smoothly with both the mouse and touch-screen drivers loadedsimultaneously, although the mouse was preferable for most operations.andP;  Itwas possible, but difficult to invoke a double-click with the touch screenwhile running OS/2.andM;Most users won't face this difficulty, though, since they will likely beworking with touch-screen-specific software.andM;The Touch Display 8516 will be available through IBM dealers startingSeptember 17, 1991.andM;IBM PS/2 Touch Display 8516andM;IBM Corp., Old Orchid Rd., Armonk, NY 10605; 800-426-2468.andM;List Price: $1,695.andM;In Short: The 8516 works with a standard VGA adapter and a PS/2 mouse port,and any input device.andP;  It should bring multimedia closer to home.andM;CIRCLE 713 ON READER SERVICE CARD</TEXT></DOC>